          <image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/graphics8-9279.jpg" id="id1165188896725__onlineimage" width="300" print-width="2in"/>
        </media>
<caption>German engineer Carl Paul Gottfried von Linde (1842 - 1934). </caption>
      </figure>




    <para id="id1165172290244">As a consequence of the use of ammonia as a refrigerant, it was possible to prepare ammonia on a large industrial scale. Ammonia prepared by the Haber-Bosch process can be converted to nitric acid by the Ostwald process developed by Wilhelm Ostwald (<link target-id="id1165183279055"/>). Treatment of ammonia with air over a platinum catalyst yields initially nitric oxide, <link target-id="eip-245"/>, and subsequently to nitrogen dioxide, <link target-id="eip-246"/>, which dissolves in water to give nitric acid, <link target-id="eip-247"/>.</para>

